{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11841"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11841"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.1,0.05,0.03,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102194"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84658"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"548"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34987"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102194"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 68-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a painless lump underneath his right eye which has been evident for about two months (Image). He has presented because it keeps bleeding and does not seem to heal. He has no other symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypopion","Chalazion","Hordeolum","Dacryocystitis","Basal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal cell carcinoma (BCC)\u003C/strong\u003E. It is the most common type of skin cancer and typically affects older, sun-damaged individuals. As such, lesions are typically on sun-exposed areas and are commonly found on the face, especially the nose, eyelids, and cheeks. Lesions can be superficial (flat) or nodular and can feature a pearly rolled edge, ulceration, and telangiectasia as seen in the image. This BCC will have to be carefully excised to prevent further growth and invasion of local tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypopyon\u003C/strong\u003E is the presence of white blood cells in the anterior chamber of the eye and usually indicates severe inflammation or infection. This would appear as a layer of white exudate that can be seen in the anterior chamber.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echalazion\u003C/strong\u003E or meibomian cyst is a mild to moderately painful lump that can be on the upper or lower eyelid caused by granulomatous inflammation within the meibomian gland. Patients can present due to cosmetic appearance, ptosis of the eyelid or obstruction of vision. Conservative measures include warm compress and massage, however, sometimes incision and drainage is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehordeolum \u003C/strong\u003Eor stye is an infection of an eyelid hair follicle on either upper or lower eyelid usually caused by staph aureus. They often appear as erythematous pustules on the eyelid margin. Styes are usually painful but conservative management is usually enough for treatment including warm compress and massage and sometimes removal of the affected eyelash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacryocystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the lacrimal sac and usually appears as a red, tender swollen area or lump at the medial canthus. It is usually caused by an obstruction where stagnation of flowing tears precipitates infection. The mainstay of treatment is antibiotics given the risk of orbital cellulitis and further complications such as fistula formation. Unstable or toxic looking patients usually need an admission for IV antibiotics. Conservative measures such as warm compress and massage can help promote drainage of the duct, however, sometimes surgical incision and drainage is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["BCC\u0027s are often found on the face and feature telangiectasia, a pearly rolled edge, and ulceration","There are a range of different conditions which present as painful lumps on or around the eyelid, many of which are usually benign"],"references":["Sun, M., et al. (2019). \u0022Eyelid lesions in general practice.\u0022 Australian Journal for General Practitioners 48: 509-514.","Cameron MC, Lee E, Hibler BP, Barker CA, Mori S, Cordova M, Nehal KS, Rossi AM. Basal cell carcinoma: Epidemiology; pathophysiology; clinical and histological subtypes; and disease associations. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2019 Feb;80(2):303-317. doi: 10.1016/j.jaad.2018.03.060. Epub 2018 May 18. Erratum in: J Am Acad Dermatol. 2021 Aug;85(2):535. PMID: 29782900.","Ali, M.J., Joshi, S.D., Naik, M.N., Honavar, S.G., 2015. Clinical Profile and Management Outcome of Acute Dacryocystitis: Two Decades of Experience in a Tertiary Eye Care Center. Seminars in Ophthalmology 30, 118\u2013123.. https://doi.org/10.3109/08820538.2013.833269","Royal Victorian Eye and Ear Hospital (2017) Clinical practice guideline - Dacryocystitis. Available at: https://eyeandear.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/Dacryocystitis-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84658"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19741"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19741"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c0511d1-e28c-4a66-8d3b-d2ac0b1332e8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c0511d1-e28c-4a66-8d3b-d2ac0b1332e8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84658"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T10:03:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T10:05:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102194"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,